SIMPLE: turgid
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Turgid
<hw>Tur"gid</hw> <pr>(t⟦ucir⟧r"j⟦icr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>turgidus</ets>, from <ets>turgere</ets> to swell.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Distended beyond the natural state by some internal
agent or expansive force; swelled; swollen; bloated; inflated; tumid; --
especially applied to an enlarged part of the body; <as>as, a
<ex>turgid</ex> limb; <ex>turgid</ex> fruit</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A bladder . . . held near the fire grew <qex>turgid</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Swelling in style or language; vainly ostentatious;
bombastic; pompous; <as>as, a <ex>turgid</ex> style of
speaking</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Tur"gid*ly</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Tur"gid*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turgidity</ent>⟦br⟧
